ğŸ§  What is BeanFactory (in simple words)?

BeanFactory is a container that:

Creates objects (beans)

Manages their lifecycle

Injects dependencies

Gives you the object when you ask for it

ğŸ‘‰ Instead of you creating objects, the container does it.

That is IoC at framework level.

ğŸ”¹ Key Difference
Before	With BeanFactory
new Student()	container.getBean(Student.class)
You manage objects	Container manages objects
Manual wiring	Automatic wiring
ğŸ§© Step 1: Same interfaces (NO change)
interface Printer {
    void print(int id, String name);
}

class ConsolePrinter implements Printer {
    public void print(int id, String name) {
        System.out.println(id + " " + name);
    }
}

ğŸ§© Step 2: Student bean (same IoC version)
class Student {
    int id;
    String name;
    Printer printer;

    public Student(int id, String name, Printer printer) {
        this.id = id;
        this.name = name;
        this.printer = printer;
    }

    void display() {
        printer.print(id, name);
    }
}

ğŸ§© Step 3: Introduce BeanFactory (Spring)

Now comes the actual BeanFactory part.

XML Configuration (beans.xml)
<beans>
    <bean id="printer" class="ConsolePrinter"/>

    <bean id="student" class="Student">
        <constructor-arg value="10"/>
        <constructor-arg value="Alice"/>
        <constructor-arg ref="printer"/>
    </bean>
</beans>


ğŸ‘‰ Container decides:

Which class to create

What constructor to use

What dependency to inject

ğŸ§© Step 4: Use BeanFactory in Main
import org.springframework.beans.factory.BeanFactory;
import org.springframework.context.support.ClassPathXmlApplicationContext;

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        BeanFactory factory =
            new ClassPathXmlApplicationContext("beans.xml");

        Student s1 = (Student) factory.getBean("student");
        s1.display();
    }
}

ğŸ¯ Why THIS is BeanFactory (important)

âœ” Objects are NOT created using new
âœ” Container manages object creation
âœ” Dependencies injected automatically
âœ” Lifecycle handled by container

ğŸ‘‰ This is Spring IoC container using BeanFactory

ğŸ§  One-line interview explanation

â€œBeanFactory is Springâ€™s IoC container that creates and manages beans and injects dependencies when requested.â€

ğŸ§  BeanFactory vs ApplicationContext (must know)
BeanFactory	ApplicationContext
Lazy initialization	Eager initialization
Lightweight	Feature-rich
Low memory	Higher memory
Core container	Enterprise container
